  "summary": "Bobby and Frankie discuss the possibility that Nicholson's death was not a suicide, despite Sylvia Baskington-French's testimony providing him with an alibi. Sylvia claimed that when the gunshot rang out, Nicholson arrived from the driveway and led her to the study window, meaning he could not have been the shooter. Bobby remains skeptical of alibis, but they decide to shift their investigation toward the Kemans, who reside at 17 Paddington St. Leonard's Garden. Frankie plans to visit them by pretending to be a political lobbyist to avoid being recognized.\n\nThe conversation turns to Moira, whom Bobby believes is in grave danger. He suggests that Nicholson had two obstacles to removing before marrying Sylvia, and with one gone, Moira is next. Bobby proposes moving Moira to a castle in Wales for her safety. Frankie agrees and plans to drive to Granchester at 10:30 to find Molly.\n\nAfter saying goodbye to a pale and exhausted Roger at Merroway Manor, Frankie and Bobby drive to Granchester. Upon arriving at the oppressive, heavily bolted house, they are met by a nurse. Dr. Nicholson informs Frankie that Moira is in a very bad state and may not survive the night.",
